that will later be named Alpha Phi Alpha. They are soon followed by a sister organization, Alpha Kappa Alpha, founded at Howard University. The
National Interfraternity Conference begins to preside over fraternities on a national level.
Around WWI, references to the word “fraternity” begin to decline in
books and literature. While many of these references are generated from
chapter histories and records, the decline reaches another low after
WWII, and continues decrease until the 1980s.
